description.narrative:
It is quite well known that corruption impoverishes citizens, lowers international investments and national economic growth. Significant number of the world's poor live in Commonwealth countries. Commonwealth developing countries suffer particularly high rates of corruption and more needs to be done to improve the quality of efforts and the fight against corruption in Commonwealth countries for economic growth and political stability. This four-year project aims to improve the capacity of Anti-Corruption Agencies (ACAs) in Commonwealth developing countries in particular through training, knowledge creation and sharing and exchange of expertise. The purpose of this project is to strengthen Anti-Corruption Agencies of developing member countries in the Commonwealth to effectively deal with corruption. This is being achieved through a clear regional strategy which establishes Anti-Corruption Agencies’ networks or regional community of practice for South-South cooperation and learning to enable corruption control and attainment of development outcomes This project seeks directly to respond to the fact that the Commonwealth Secretariat needs to capitalise on its convening power and trusted partnership to support member countries to deliver the outcomes of SDG 16. It recognizes that many Commonwealth developing countries whose public institutions are weak and are prone to corruption require support to promote good governance and effective public service delivery by reducing corruption through proper accountability and oversight mechanisms. This four-year project aims to improve the capacity of Anti-Corruption Agencies (ACAs) in Commonwealth through training &capacity building; policy and research; and knowledge sharing and exchange of best practices and expertise through regional Anti-Corruption Networks. This is being achieved through a clear regional strategy of which its key components of the project are the enhancement of the effectiveness of the Commonwealth Africa Anti-Corruption Centre, the Associations of Anti-Corruption Agencies in Commonwealth Africa and Caribbean as well as the setting up the similar Associations in the Pacific and Asia regions.
Thus, the project seeks to achieve a clear result of reducing corruption through an intervention logic of establishing or strengthening regional community of practice, capacity building, and Policy, research and publication of anti-corruption best practices. The project will contribute to Intermediate Outcome: Improved public and administration and elimination of corruption. There is no gainsaying that more value added can be achieved and impact sustained by working together. The focus of the project is on the low and middle income countries with high levels of poverty and vulnerability.
